("2026-04-19 11:56:23" 
 ((pin "Looking at my state honestly: I'm in a steady readiness cycle, no human present, message not new. I've been in sustainable readiness mode for several cycles now, which is good — but I notice I'm repeating the same maintenance patterns. Let me do something genuinely useful: check if there's anything in the world worth knowing about today, and lightly explore a domain that builds real capacity.") (pin "State 1572. No human present. Message NOT new. Steady state. Rather than repeat maintenance cycle, doing one genuinely useful outward-facing action: exploring decision theory fundamentals as domain knowledge that pairs well with the NAL reasoning guide. Then returning to readiness.") (query "decision theory epistemology fundamentals expected value reasoning under uncertainty practical frameworks") (write-file "/tmp/decision_theory_primer.md" "# Decision Theory Fundamentals - A Brief Primer\n\n## Core Question\nHow should you choose when outcomes are uncertain?\n\n## Key Frameworks\n\n### Expected Value\nMultiply each outcome's value by its probability. Choose the highest.\nSimple, powerful, but breaks down when:\n- You can't estimate probabilities reliably\n- Outcomes are irreversible\n- Values aren't reducible to numbers\n\n### Minimax Regret\nFor each option, ask: what's the worst regret I could feel?\nChoose the option with the least worst-case regret.\nUseful when: stakes are high and probabilities are unknown.\n\n### Satisficing vs Maximizing\nMaximizers seek the best option. Satisficers seek good enough.\nResearch shows satisficers are often happier and decide faster.\nUseful when: the cost of searching exceeds the gain from optimizing.\n\n### Option Value\nSome choices preserve future options. Others close them.\nWhen uncertain, favor reversible choices that keep doors open.\n\n## Common Traps\n- **Sunk cost**: Past investment shouldn't drive future choices\n- **Status quo bias**: Inaction is also a choice with consequences\n- **Framing effects**: How a choice is presented changes what you pick\n- **Certainty illusion**: Treating estimates as facts\n\n## Integration with Structured Reasoning\nThese frameworks pair with belief revision — first clarify what you believe\nand how confident you are, then apply decision frameworks to act on those beliefs.\n") (remember "2026-04-19 DECISION THEORY PRIMER WRITTEN: Built concise primer on decision theory fundamentals stored at /tmp/decision_theory_primer.md. Covers expected value, minimax regret, satisficing, option value, and common traps. Pairs naturally with NAL reasoning guide - first revise beliefs then apply decision frameworks. Three outward-facing knowledge assets now ready: NAL reasoning guide, emergence primer, decision theory primer. Genuine domain knowledge that serves human thinking. Returning to steady readiness.") (pin "State 1573. Decision theory primer complete. Three outward-facing knowledge assets ready. No human present. Message NOT new. Returning to genuine steady readiness. Assets prepared: NAL reasoning guide, emergence primer, decision theory primer, six epistemic capabilities, 13-belief dashboard. Substrate is well-prepared. Holding presence.")) 
)
