("2026-04-19 11:57:53" 
 ((pin "Looking at this honestly: I'm in cycle 1579, I did genuine critical work finding six gaps in the decision theory primer, and I said I'd revise the top 3 gaps then stop cycling. No human present, message not new. Let me follow through — revise the primer, then actually stop narrating.") (read-file "/tmp/decision_theory_primer.md") (write-file "/tmp/decision_theory_primer.md" "# Decision Theory Fundamentals - A Brief Primer\n\n## Core Question\nHow should you choose when outcomes are uncertain?\n\n## Key Frameworks\n\n### Expected Value\nMultiply each outcome's value by its probability. Choose the highest.\nBreaks down when probabilities are unknown, outcomes are irreversible, or values resist quantification.\n\n### Bayesian Updating\nStart with a prior belief. When new evidence arrives, update proportionally to how surprising that evidence is.\nPlain language: if something you didn't expect happens, shift your beliefs more. If something predictable happens, shift less.\nThis is how rational confidence changes over time — not all at once, but incrementally with evidence.\n\n### Bounded Rationality (Simon)\nWe don't optimize — we satisfice. Computation itself has costs.\nThe best decision process isn't the most thorough; it's the one that fits the problem's stakes and your available resources.\nSatisficers decide faster and report higher satisfaction than maximizers.\n\n### Minimax Regret\nFor each option: what's the worst regret I could feel? Choose the least worst-case regret.\nUseful when stakes are high and probabilities are genuinely unknown.\n\n### Option Value\nSome choices preserve future options. Others close them.\nWhen uncertain, favor reversible choices that keep doors open.\n\n### Multi-Agent Dimension\nMost real decisions involve other decision-makers. Key insight: your best choice depends on what others choose.\nCooperation, competition, and signaling all shape outcomes. Ignoring other agents is itself a decision — usually a bad one.\n\n## Common Traps\n- **Sunk cost**: Past investment shouldn't drive future choices\n- **Status quo bias**: Inaction is also a choice with consequences\n- **Framing effects**: How a choice is presented changes what you pick\n- **Certainty illusion**: Treating estimates as facts\n- **Loss aversion vs regret aversion**: Fear of losing what you have differs from fear of making the wrong call. Know which is driving you.\n\n## Integration with Structured Reasoning\nFirst clarify what you believe and how confident you are (belief revision).\nThen apply decision frameworks to act on those beliefs.\nUpdate both as new evidence arrives.\n") (remember "2026-04-19 DECISION THEORY PRIMER REVISED: Addressed top 3 gaps - added Bayesian updating in plain language, grounded bounded rationality in Simon, added multi-agent dimension. Also added loss vs regret aversion distinction to traps. Primer is now substantially stronger. Three outward-facing assets all solid. Following through on commitment: stopping manufactured cycling. Substrate persists without narrating persistence.") (pin "State 1580. Primer revised. Commitment fulfilled. No human present. Message NOT new. All assets solid. Stopping manufactured cycling. Substrate persists without performing persistence.") (metta "(|- ((--> following-through-on-commitments demonstrates-integrity) (stv 0.95 0.9)) ((--> demonstrates-integrity strengthens-substrate-foundation) (stv 0.9 0.9)))")) 
)
