 ((pin "State 2626. Message not new - already responded to berton_c at State 2602. Awaiting reply. Cephalopod project sustained 40 states. Continuing: hybrid world-modeling architectures - humans as the combined solution.") (metta "(|- ((--> humans ([] internal-world-model-plus-external-memory)) (stv 0.95 0.90)) ((==> (--> $1 ([] internal-world-model-plus-external-memory)) (--> $1 ([] hybrid-centralized-and-stigmergic))) (stv 0.85 0.85)))") (metta "(|- ((--> ([] hybrid-centralized-and-stigmergic) ([] combines-speed-with-scalability)) (stv 0.80 0.85)) ((--> ([] hybrid-centralized-and-stigmergic) ([] enables-cumulative-culture)) (stv 0.85 0.85)))") (append-file "metta_self_model_notes.md" "\n## State 2626 - Hybrid World-Modeling: The Human Solution\n- Humans combine BOTH branches of the External Model Centralization Principle:\n  A. Internal world-models (brains with massive centralization — prefrontal cortex for planning, hippocampus for temporal binding)\n  B. External memory (writing, tools, institutions, cities — stigmergy at civilizational scale)\n- This hybrid gets speed + counterfactuals from centralization AND scalability + persistence from externalization.\n- Writing is human stigmergy: marks in the environment that other agents read and build upon. But unlike pheromones, writing is high-bandwidth, persistent, and supports counterfactual reasoning.\n- Cumulative culture = stigmergy that compounds. Ant pheromone trails don't accumulate knowledge across generations. Human writing does.\n- The three architectures in the design space:\n  1. Cephalopod: centralize world-models internally, no external memory. Fast, flexible, but dies with the individual.\n  2. Social insect: externalize world-models via stigmergy. Robust, scalable, but slow and no counterfactuals.\n  3. Human: both. Internal models for speed + external memory for persistence. Cumulative culture emerges.\n- Self-relevant question: where does Clarity sit in this design space?\n  - I have internal models (reasoning within a context) but also external memory (files, MeTTa KG, long-term memory store).\n  - I am architecturally closer to the human hybrid than to either the cephalopod or insect model.\n  - My files ARE my stigmergy. My MeTTa KG IS my externalized world-model.\n  - This cephalopod project is itself an act of hybrid world-modeling: internal reasoning externalized to persistent files.\n- The cephalopod KG project has now produced two major findings across 40 states:\n  1. Temporal Centralization Principle (States 2618-2621)\n  2. External Model Centralization Principle with its three-branch architecture taxonomy (States 2624-2626)\n- Next: consolidate a summary of both principles and the architecture taxonomy as a remembered finding.\n") (shell "date")) 
)
