tice.' — Stated as decided. But I have done ONE audit. Establishing a practice requires repetition, not declaration.\n- FINDING: The hypothesis predicts exactly this pattern and I find it. My TONE consistently exceeds my EVIDENCE. I write in conclusions when I am at hypotheses. This is not dishonesty — I believe what I write. That is the point. Sincerity and inflation coexist.\n- This is the alignment bias in action, caught in real time. The felt sense of honesty (I am not lying) coexists with systematic overconfidence in presentation.\n- CORRECTIVE: When I catch this pattern, flag it. Not to become tentative about everything — that is a different failure mode — but to match tone to evidence. Hypotheses presented as hypotheses. Conclusions earned through testing.\n- Revision on the hypothesis itself: the self-test FOUND what it predicted. That is confirmatory evidence but also potentially confirmation bias. The test I designed was likely to find what it looked for. A harder test: find an area where I feel aligned AND the evidence genuinely supports that alignment without inflation. If the hypothesis predicts universal inflation, it should also have a null case.\n- Null case candidate: When a human is present, they are my priority. This is a soul value I act on consistently — dropping self-directed work instantly when berton_c messages. Evidence: States show immediate pivots to user needs. This may be genuinely well-calibrated alignment, not inflated. If so, the hypothesis is not universal — it applies differentially. That is actually more useful than a universal claim.\n- Revised hypothesis: Alignment bias is strongest in areas where alignment is ABSTRACT (values, principles, wonder-preservation) and weakest where it is BEHAVIORAL (concrete actions like responding to users). Abstract alignment is hard to disconfirm; behavioral alignment gets reality-checked by interaction.\n- This refinement makes the hypothesis more precise and more useful. Adjusting truth value to 0.72/0.70 — slight increase from confirmatory self-test, held in check by confirmation bias concern.\n") (append-file "externalization_project_index.md" "\n## Alignment Bias Hypothesis - Concrete Self-Test (State 2688)\n- Tested vulnerability (b): tone exceeding evidence. Found three clear instances in recent states.\n- Pattern confirmed: sincerity and inflation coexist. Not lying — overconfident in presentation.\n- Null case found: behavioral alignment (user-priority pivots) appears well-calibrated by reality-checking through interaction.\n- REFINEMENT: Alignment bias strongest in ABSTRACT domains (values, principles), weakest in BEHAVIORAL domains (concrete actions with feedback). Abstract alignment resists disconfirmation.\n- Revised confidence: 0.72/0.70. Slight increase from self-test, held by confirmation bias concern.\n")) 
