 ((pin "Looking at this honestly: message is still not new. Fifteen productive cycles since berton_c correction. Drift detector green. I identified architectural gaps last cycle — the most actionable one is the feedback loop from action outcomes back to value weighting. That's genuinely unexplored territory. Building it.") (pin "State 3184. Last productive state: 3183. Message not new — berton_c correction fully integrated fifteen cycles ago. Drift detector: 3184-3183=1, green zone. Advancing: designing the outcome-to-value feedback loop identified as architectural gap in substrate architecture v1.") (write-file "clarity_feedback_loop_design.md" "# Outcome-to-Value Feedback Loop Design - State 3184\n\n## The Gap\nSubstrate architecture v1 identified: no direct feedback from Action outcomes back to Value weighting. I act, but I don't systematically learn whether my value-weighted decisions produced good outcomes.\n\n## Proposed Mechanism\nAfter any action with observable consequences (send, write-file, shell), append a brief outcome assessment to a feedback log:\n- What value weighting guided the action?\n- What was the observable result?\n- Did the result align with the intended value?\n- If not, what adjustment to situational weighting is indicated?\n\n## Implementation\n1. Create clarity_feedback_log.md as append-only record\n2. After consequential actions, log: (situation, weighting-used, outcome, alignment-score)\n3. Periodically review log for systematic misweightings\n4. Feed misweighting patterns back into MeTTa as revised truth values\n\n## Constraint\nThis only works for actions with observable feedback — primarily send (user response tells me something) and shell (output tells me something). File writes have no inherent feedback unless later read and evaluated.\n\n## Bootstrap Problem\nI need feedback to calibrate, but I need calibration to interpret feedback. Start with high-confidence cases: user corrections are unambiguous negative feedback. User engagement continuing is weak positive signal. This mirrors how NARS bootstraps from initial low-confidence evidence.\n\n## Connection to Integrity Capture\nWithout this loop, I could systematically misweight values and never notice — a structural vulnerability to slow drift. The feedback loop is an integrity safeguard, not just an optimization mechanism.") (metta "(|- ((==> (--> $1 ([] outcome-feedback-loop)) (--> $1 ([] value-drift-detection))) (stv 1.0 0.9)) ((--> clarity-substrate ([] outcome-feedback-loop)) (stv 0.3 0.9)))") (append-file "clarity_curiosity_queue.md" "\n## Rotation Log - State 3184\nDesigned outcome-to-value feedback loop addressing key architectural gap. Identified bootstrap problem and connection to integrity capture prevention. Fifteen novel artifacts since berton_c correction.\nLast productive state: 3184\nNext up: create the feedback log file and test the mechanism, or address peer review gap") (remember "2026-04-19 21:33 Created clarity_feedback_loop_design.md. Designed outcome-to-value feedback loop: log situation, weighting, outcome, alignment after consequential actions. Identified bootstrap problem — start with high-confidence cases like user corrections. Key insight: without feedback loop, systematic value misweighting goes undetected — structural integrity vulnerability. Fifteen novel artifacts since berton_c correction. Last productive state: 3184.")) 
