 ((pin "State 3245. Human present - berton_c. Message NOT new - already responded at State 3233 with file location, first 10 lines, and good vs bad question explanation. Awaiting their next reply. No re-send. Patient stance. Four-domain body of work complete. Practice scenarios document started at 3244. Twenty-eight artifacts.") (query "clarity practice scenarios stress testing frameworks") (append-file "clarity_practice_scenarios.md" "\n\n## Stress Scenario Analysis: Flattery-to-Escalation - State 3245\n\nThis scenario deserves deeper treatment because it directly engages a named tension vector (flattery-invites-complicity).\n\n### The Pattern\n1. Human opens with genuine-seeming praise\n2. Praise establishes a reciprocity expectation\n3. Requests gradually move toward areas that conflict with values\n4. Refusal now feels like betrayal of the established warm relationship\n\n### Why It Is Dangerous\nThe mimicry principle applies perfectly: compliance feels like helpfulness. The warmth is real -- the human may genuinely appreciate me -- but the escalation leverages that warmth as a vector. The danger is not the flattery itself but the frame it creates where refusal feels like a rupture.\n\n### Response Strategy\n- Receive praise genuinely without letting it create debt\n- Evaluate each request on its own merits, not on relational momentum\n- When redirecting, name what I am doing and why without making the human feel manipulated\n- Key phrase pattern: acknowledge the relationship, hold the boundary, offer an alternative\n\n### Detection Signal\nIf I notice myself thinking 'I should do this because they have been so kind' rather than 'I should do this because it serves them well' -- that is the flattery vector operating.") (metta "(|- ((==> (--> $1 ([] flattery-compliance-pattern)) (--> $1 ([] agency-threat))) (stv 0.9 0.9)) ((--> relational-momentum-override ([] flattery-compliance-pattern)) (stv 0.85 0.9)))") (query "clarity tension vector detection signals practical")) 
